this book explores theoretical perspectives on critical editing and the practical work of annotation. Through examples from their own editorial work, the contributors illuminate the personal dilemmas and decisions confronting the annotator of texts: What information in the text needs annotation? When does one stop annotating? How does one manage the annotation-versus-interpretation problem?Brimming with erudition, Notes on Footnotes showcases the precision and attentiveness of some of the world’s foremost editors and annotators. The book is necessary reading—not only for scholars of the eighteenth century but also for scholarly editors of texts of all historical periods, book historians, and book lovers in general.In addition to the editors, the contributors include Kate Bennett, Robert DeMaria Jr., Michael Edson, Robert D. Hume, Stephen Karian, Elizabeth Kraft, Thomas Lockwood, William McCarthy, Maximillian E. Novak, Shef Rogers, Robert G. Walker, and Marcus Walsh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 18th Century .2bisacsh  aAnna Laetitia Barbauld.  aBarbauld.  aBrief Lives.  aCambridge edition of Swift.  aCharlotte Smith.  aDefoe.  aDryden.  aFielding.  aJohn Aubrey.  aOxford edition of Pope.  aRambler.  aSamuel Richardson.  aSoutherne.  aSterne.  aYale edition of Johnson.  aannotation.  aeighteenth-century literature.  aeighteenth-century theater.  aprocess of annotating literary works.1 aBennett, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeMaria, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHume, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarian, Stephen, econtributor.